Perfeito! Agora tenho uma visão completa da estrutura. Deixa eu compilar um relatório abrangente:

## Relatório: Esquema SQLite-vec para HQ

Explorei a arquitetura de banco de dados do projeto HQ. Aqui está a estrutura completa para adicionar tabelas sqlite-vec (embeddings):

### 1. **Padrão de Organização Atual (SCHEMA_SQL)**

A base segue um padrão de 4 níveis:

**Nível 1: Metadata**
```rust
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS schema_metadata (
    key TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
    value TEXT NOT NULL
) WITHOUT ROWID;
```

**Nível 2: Core Tables** (source tables)
```rust
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS project_tasks (
    id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,          // ULID (26 chars)
    title TEXT NOT NULL,
    description TEXT,
    status TEXT NOT NULL,         // CHECK constraint
    category TEXT,
    sort_order REAL NOT NULL,
    is_passed TEXT NOT NULL,      // 'true'/'false' strings
    created_at TEXT NOT NULL,     // RFC3339 timestamps
    updated_at TEXT NOT NULL
);

CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS project_progress (
    id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,          // Composite: session#{id}#{id}
    content TEXT NOT NULL,
    created_at TEXT NOT NULL      // Note: NO WITHOUT ROWID (needed for FTS5)
);
```

**Nível 3: Indexes**
```rust
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_project_tasks_status ON project_tasks(status);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_project_tasks_created_at ON project_tasks(created_at);
// Fractional sort_order enables reordering without overwrites
```

**Nível 4: FTS5 Virtual Tables** (existing pattern)
```rust
CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE IF NOT EXISTS project_tasks_fts USING fts5(
    title,
    description,
    category,
    content='project_tasks',      // Link to source table
    content_rowid='rowid'         // Use implicit rowid
);

CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE IF NOT EXISTS project_progress_fts USING fts5(
    content,
    content='project_progress',
    content_rowid='rowid'
);
```

### 2. **Padrão de Sincronização com Triggers (FTS5_TRIGGERS_SQL)**

Cada tabela recebe 3 triggers (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE):

```rust
CREATE TRIGGER IF NOT EXISTS project_tasks_fts_insert AFTER INSERT ON project_tasks BEGIN
    INSERT INTO project_tasks_fts(rowid, title, description, category)
    VALUES (NEW.rowid, NEW.title, NEW.description, NEW.category);
END;

CREATE TRIGGER IF NOT EXISTS project_tasks_fts_update AFTER UPDATE ON project_tasks BEGIN
    // Delete old entry
    INSERT INTO project_tasks_fts(project_tasks_fts, rowid, title, description, category)
    VALUES('delete', OLD.rowid, OLD.title, OLD.description, OLD.category);
    // Insert new entry
    INSERT INTO project_tasks_fts(rowid, title, description, category)
    VALUES (NEW.rowid, NEW.title, NEW.description, NEW.category);
END;

CREATE TRIGGER IF NOT EXISTS project_tasks_fts_delete AFTER DELETE ON project_tasks BEGIN
    INSERT INTO project_tasks_fts(project_tasks_fts, rowid, title, description, category)
    VALUES('delete', OLD.rowid, OLD.title, OLD.description, OLD.category);
END;
```

**Padrão crítico:**
- `rowid` vinculação automática entre source e virtual table
- Triggers executados AFTER (não há BEFORE triggers)
- UPDATE é delete + insert (reindex completo)

### 3. **CRUD Pattern com FTS5 Search**

**Search Implementation** (tasks.rs linha 231-256):
```rust
pub fn search_tasks(conn: &Connection, query: &str) -> DbResult<Vec<ProjectTask>> {
    let mut stmt = conn.prepare(
        r#"
        SELECT p.id, p.title, p.description, p.status, p.category, p.sort_order, p.is_passed, p.created_at, p.updated_at
        FROM project_tasks p
        JOIN project_tasks_fts fts ON p.rowid = fts.rowid
        WHERE project_tasks_fts MATCH ?1
        ORDER BY rank
        LIMIT ?2
        "#,
    )?;
    // ... execute and collect rows
}
```

**Key points:**
- JOIN via `rowid` (implicit in FTS5)
- MATCH operator para queries
- `rank` ordering (built-in FTS5 scoring)

### 4. **Fluxo de Inicialização**

```rust
pub fn init_schema(conn: &Connection) -> DbResult<()> {
    // Step 1: Pragmas (concurrency + sync)
    conn.execute_batch(PRAGMAS)?;

    // Step 2: Core tables + indexes
    conn.execute_batch(SCHEMA_SQL)?;

    // Step 3: Virtual tables (FTS5)
    conn.execute_batch(FTS5_SCHEMA_SQL)?;

    // Step 4: Triggers (sync FTS with source)
    conn.execute_batch(FTS5_TRIGGERS_SQL)?;

    // Step 5: Version metadata
    conn.execute(
        "INSERT OR REPLACE INTO schema_metadata (key, value) VALUES ('version', ?1)",
        [SCHEMA_VERSION],
    )?;

    Ok(())
}
```

**Importante:** Cada constant string é executada com `execute_batch()` - critical para script SQL múltiplas linhas.

### 5. **Estrutura para Adicionar SQLite-vec Virtual Tables**

Para embeddings, você seguiria este padrão:

```rust
// Novo constant (adicionar em schema.rs)
pub const EMBEDDINGS_SCHEMA_SQL: &str = r#"
-- ============================================================================
-- EMBEDDING VECTOR TABLES (sqlite-vec)
-- ============================================================================

-- Embeddings para task descriptions
CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE IF NOT EXISTS project_tasks_embeddings USING vec0(
    id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
    embedding float[1536],        // OpenAI ada-002 dims
    content='project_tasks',
    content_rowid='rowid'
);

-- Embeddings para progress content
CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE IF NOT EXISTS project_progress_embeddings USING vec0(
    id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
    embedding float[1536],
    content='project_progress',
    content_rowid='rowid'
);
"#;

pub const EMBEDDINGS_TRIGGERS_SQL: &str = r#"
-- Sync triggers para embeddings
CREATE TRIGGER IF NOT EXISTS project_tasks_embeddings_insert AFTER INSERT ON project_tasks BEGIN
    INSERT INTO project_tasks_embeddings(rowid, id, embedding)
    VALUES (NEW.rowid, NEW.id, NULL);  -- Embeddings populados via app
END;

CREATE TRIGGER IF NOT EXISTS project_tasks_embeddings_delete AFTER DELETE ON project_tasks BEGIN
    DELETE FROM project_tasks_embeddings WHERE rowid = OLD.rowid;
END;

-- Similar para project_progress...
"#;

pub fn init_schema(conn: &Connection) -> DbResult<()> {
    // ... existing code ...

    // Add after FTS5 init
    conn.execute_batch(EMBEDDINGS_SCHEMA_SQL)?;
    conn.execute_batch(EMBEDDINGS_TRIGGERS_SQL)?;

    Ok(())
}
```

### 6. **Padrões-Chave Observados**

| Aspecto | Padrão |
|---------|--------|
| **IDs** | ULID 26-char (CHECK constraint), suporta GLOB para composite IDs |
| **Timestamps** | RFC3339 strings (chrono::DateTime parsing) |
| **Booleans** | Strings 'true'/'false' (compatibilidade SQL) |
| **Virtual Tables** | `content=` + `content_rowid=rowid` linkage |
| **Triggers** | AFTER triggers, UPDATE = DELETE + INSERT |
| **Sync** | Automático via triggers, sem client-side sync |
| **Search** | JOIN + MATCH + rank ordering |
| **Idempotência** | Todos CREATE TABLE/INDEX/TRIGGER IF NOT EXISTS |
| **Pagination** | Cursor-based com encoded IDs (base64) |

### 7. **Dependências Relevantes (Cargo.toml)**

```toml
rusqlite = { version = "0.38.0", features = ["bundled"] }
ulid = { version = "1.2.1", features = ["serde"] }
chrono = { version = "0.4.42", features = ["serde"] }
```

Para sqlite-vec, você precisaria adicionar:
```toml
sqlite-vec = "0.1.x"  // ou versão compatível
```

### 8. **Próximos Passos para Implementação**

1. **Extension Loading**: verificar como carregar sqlite-vec extension no rusqlite
2. **Embedding Generation**: integrar OpenAI API ou modelo local
3. **Vector Search CRUD**: adicionar funções Rust no módulo de tasks/progress
4. **Migration Path**: versionamento de schema para adicionar embeddings a DBs existentes
5. **Testing**: padrão de testes em-memory com schema completo (veja `schema.rs` testes)

---

**Conclusão:** O projeto usa um padrão muito robusto de virtual tables sincronizadas via triggers. SQLite-vec seguiria a mesma arquitetura, com `vec0` no lugar de `fts5`. Os triggers precisam ser ajustados para preencher valores null inicialmente (já que embeddings vêm do app, não do user).
